<p>
Today I learnt a great tip <a href="https://github.com/clojure-emacs/nrepl.el/issues/382">here</a> via <a href="http://www.sanityinc.com/">Steve Purcell</a>. If you want to get
the absolute latest build of an Emacs package, without waiting for the
MELPA rebuild cycle to take place, just:
</p>

<ol class="org-ol">
<li>Clone <a href="https://github.com/milkypostman/melpa.git">the Melpa repo</a>.
</li>
<li>Open the <code>recipes/</code> file in emacs.
</li>
<li>Accept the <code>dir-locals</code> warning.
</li>
<li><code>M-x package-build-current-recipe</code> to evaluate that recipe locally and install the latest package.
</li>
</ol>

<p>
I must remember that one&#x2026;
</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/KrisJenkinsBlog/~4/xo-f8s-Bals" height="1" width="1"/>